HashMap is a hash‑based unordered container with average O(1) insert/lookup, while BTreeMap maintains ordered keys (B+ tree) giving O(log n) operations. They differ mainly in ordering and memory layout.

Example:
let map = HashMap::new();
map.insert("a", 1);
let mut btree = BTreeMap::new();
btree.insert("b", 2);
btree.iter().for_each(|(k,_)| {}) // iterates sorted

The main reason to use BTreeMap when you don’t need ordering is that you get an ordered iteration if later required. It isn’t intrinsically slower for lookups; both have similar average costs, and the extra memory overhead of the tree is a trade‑off for ordering.

Example:
let mut btree = BTreeMap::new();
btree.insert(3, "three");
btree.insert(1, "one"); // will be stored as 1: "one", 3: "three"
btree.iter().map(|(k,v)| (k,v)).collect::<Vec<_>>()

HashSet uses a hash table with chaining; collisions are resolved quickly and generally give O(1) average insertion. BTreeSet is a balanced BST, so each insert is O(log n). For many random inserts, HashSet usually wins.

Benchmark:
use rand::seq::SliceRandom;
let mut set = HashSet::new();
for _ in 0..10_000 {
    let v: i32 = rand::random::<i32>();
    set.insert(v);
}
println!("HashSet size: {}", set.len());

use std::collections::{BTreeSet, HashSet};
let mut bset = BTreeSet::new();
for _ in 0..10_000 {
    let v: i32 = rand::random::<i32>();
    bset.insert(v);
}
println!("BTreeSet size: {}", bset.len());

